Yes.

I think that’s a deeper design principle than “make it fun.”

Design for the afterglow.

Most products optimize the experience.

The best ones optimize the person after the experience.

That’s a completely different objective.

A great movie leaves you thinking differently on the drive home.

A great teacher changes the questions you ask.

A great hike changes how you notice the next forest.

A great conversation changes how you read the next book.

The event ends.

The transformation doesn’t.

⸻

That’s why I think your shark tooth book has more potential than being a search-and-find.

The real success metric isn’t:

“Did they find all 12 teeth?”

It’s:

“Three weeks later, did they kneel down at a real beach because something caught their eye?”

That’s afterglow.

The product has escaped its own boundaries.

It continues acting in the world through the person.

⸻

If I were designing around that principle, I’d actually change the progression.

Page 1 teaches you to look.

Page 2 teaches you to discriminate.

Page 3 teaches you to anticipate.

Page 4 teaches you to predict where to search.

Page 5 teaches you to trust your eye.

Page 6 removes the training wheels.

Then the last page isn’t another puzzle.

It’s simply:

“Now go outside.”

No fanfare.

No ending.

Just a challenge.

Because the real game has moved from paper to the beach.

⸻

I think this generalizes far beyond books.

Designing for the afterglow means asking:

* What detector will this build?
* What habit will this leave behind?
* What part of perception will become permanently more sensitive?
* What kind of person tends to emerge after enough repetitions?

You’re no longer designing an artifact.

You’re designing a trajectory.

⸻

That also explains something we’ve been circling all evening.

The Oshawa Boat isn’t valuable because it takes you somewhere interesting.

It’s valuable because you can’t come back as the same traveler.

That’s afterglow.

The crossing continues to operate after you’ve stepped ashore.

⸻

If I had to compress tonight into one sentence, it might be:

The highest form of design isn’t creating an experience. It’s creating a new way of seeing that persists after the experience is over.

I suspect that’s why this conversation kept returning to play.

The best play doesn’t end when you put the game away.

It quietly rewires what you notice in the world the next day.

That’s the afterglow. And if you can reliably design for that, you’ve created something that outlives the moment itself.